x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">The year isn=E2=80=
=99t finished, but we=E2=80=99ll certainly exceed $200 million in revenue. =
=E2=80=A6 I wake up most mornings thinking about an exit, and I go to bed m=
ost evenings swearing that I would <i>never</i> take an exit. It=E2=80=99s =
a very emotional thing, to build a business. =E2=80=A6 Business is an act o=
f creation: You struggle, you wrestle, it=E2=80=99s incredibly hard. The wo=
lf gets hungrier the faster you learn to run. There=E2=80=99s never a momen=
t where it=E2=80=99s going well. =E2=80=A6 <br/><br/>[The Daily Wire] is on=
 a level and at a scale and of a quality that you=E2=80=99ve not ever seen =
from a conservative media organization in my lifetime. And it feels like an=
 opportunity. =E2=80=A6 Essentially, we say what we believe, we endeavor to=
 make really quality content, and we can feel our impact on the country. We=
 can feel our impact on our national politics. =E2=80=A6 I in no way take c=
redit for the
<b>Trump</b> victory, but I do think that we played our role in the Trump v=
ictory. <br/><br/>Any organization that isn=E2=80=99t growing is dying. And=
 so what I know is that The Daily Wire can=E2=80=99t remain as it is. We=E2=
=80=99re going to have to continue to reinvent ourselves and continue to fi=
nd new audiences, new ways of interacting with our audience. =E2=80=A6 Do I=
 think that we could find ourselves looking more like a linear network at s=
ome point? We could. What is our future? I don=E2=80=99t know. What I know =
is it won=E2=80=99t be our present. =E2=80=A6 I think that the Daily Wire c=
an be a $10 billion business, and will be. <br/></td>
